(43, 11, 28, 38, 3, 10, 10, 'calleth for thee', 'Calling and Community', 'This connection highlights the theme of calling individuals to community. In John 11:28, Mary is called by her sister, while Zechariah 3:10 speaks of calling neighbors together under the vine and fig tree.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 28, 40, 26, 18, 18, 'The Master is come, and calleth for thee', 'Call of the Master', 'This connection highlights the theme of the Master calling for his followers. In both passages, the term ''Master'' is used to signify authority and invitation, emphasizing the relationship between Jesus and those who respond to him.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 28, 41, 14, 14, 14, 'The Master', 'Connection of ''The Master'' Theme', 'Both passages emphasize the presence of ''The Master'' calling for action. In John, the Master calls for Mary, while in Mark, the Master instructs his disciples regarding preparations for Passover.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 29, 19, 27, 8, 8, 'arose quickly, and came unto him', 'Seeking and Response', 'This connection highlights the theme of seeking and responding to a call. In both passages, there is an immediate action taken in response to a directive, emphasizing the importance of seeking the Lord''s presence.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 29, 20, 15, 23, 23, 'arose quickly', 'Response to Timely Words', 'This connection highlights the importance of timely responses. In John 11:29, the quick action of coming to Jesus reflects the joy and goodness of a timely response, as noted in Proverbs 15:23.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 29, 22, 3, 1, 4, 'arose quickly', 'Seeking the Beloved', 'Both passages emphasize the urgency of seeking the beloved. In John 11:29, the act of rising quickly parallels the speaker''s determination to find their beloved in Song of Solomon 3:1-4.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 29, 19, 119, 59, 60, 'arose quickly', 'Haste in Response to Calling', 'This connection highlights the theme of urgency in responding to a call. Both passages emphasize the quickness of action, as seen in ''arose quickly'' and ''made haste''.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 29, 20, 27, 17, 17, 'arose quickly', 'Response to Call and Growth', 'This connection highlights the theme of responsiveness and mutual encouragement. In John 11:29, the quick response signifies readiness to engage, while Proverbs 27:17 emphasizes the sharpening effect friends have on one another, suggesting that such interactions foster growth.', 'theme', 0.3, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 30, 43, 11, 20, 20, 'where Martha met him', 'Martha''s Encounter with Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize Martha''s action of meeting Jesus. In John 11:20, Martha goes to meet him, while John 11:30 notes that Jesus was in the place where Martha met him. This connection highlights the significance of their interaction.', 'parallel', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 31, 43, 11, 19, 19, 'comforted her', 'Connection of Mourning and Comfort', 'Both passages emphasize the presence of the Jews who came to comfort Martha and Mary in their grief over their brother''s death. The actions of the Jews in both verses highlight the communal aspect of mourning and support during times of loss.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 31, 1, 37, 35, 35, 'to the grave to weep there', 'Expressions of Mourning', 'Both passages emphasize the act of mourning and the response of those around the grieving individuals. In John 11:31, Mary is followed by those who believe she is going to weep at the grave, while in Genesis 37:35, Jacob refuses comfort as he mourns for his son.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 31, 10, 12, 16, 18, 'to weep there', 'Expressions of Grief and Mourning', 'Both passages emphasize the act of mourning in response to death. In John, Mary is followed by others to the grave to weep, while in 2 Samuel, David''s refusal to eat reflects his deep sorrow over his child''s death.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 31, 46, 2, 15, 15, NULL, 'Judgment and Spiritual Insight', 'This connection highlights the theme of judgment in both passages. In John 11:31, the crowd''s perception of Mary reflects a limited understanding, while 1 Corinthians 2:15 emphasizes that spiritual individuals discern deeper truths beyond human judgment.', 'theme', 0.307, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 32, 43, 11, 21, 21, 'if thou hadst been here, my brother had not died', 'Expressions of Grief and Faith', 'Both passages emphasize the sentiment of grief and faith in Jesus'' ability to heal. Mary and Martha express a similar belief that if Jesus had been present, their brother would not have died.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 32, 42, 5, 8, 8, 'fell down at his feet', 'Expressions of Humility Before Jesus', 'This connection highlights the theme of humility in both passages, as Mary and Peter both fall down before Jesus. Their actions express deep reverence and recognition of Jesus'' authority and power.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 32, 42, 17, 16, 16, 'fell down at his feet', 'Expressions of Humility and Faith', 'This connection highlights the act of falling down at Jesus'' feet in both passages, demonstrating humility and reverence. Both Mary and the Samaritan express their deep emotions and faith in Jesus through this physical gesture.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 32, 66, 5, 8, 8, 'fell down at his feet', 'Falling Down Before Jesus', 'This connection highlights the act of falling down before Jesus in both passages. Mary falls at Jesus'' feet in grief, while the elders and beasts fall before the Lamb in worship, emphasizing reverence and submission.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 32, 66, 5, 14, 14, 'fell down at his feet', 'Worship and Submission', 'This connection highlights the act of falling down, which signifies deep reverence and submission in both passages. Mary falls at Jesus'' feet in grief, while the elders worship Him in reverence.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 32, 43, 11, 37, 37, 'if thou hadst been here', 'Connection of Grief and Power', 'This connection highlights the theme of grief expressed by Mary and the questioning of Jesus'' power to prevent death. Both passages emphasize the belief that Jesus could have intervened to save Lazarus, showcasing the tension between faith and despair.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 33, 43, 11, 38, 38, 'groaned in the spirit', 'Jesus'' Emotional Response', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' emotional state as he experiences deep sorrow. The repeated phrase ''groaning in the spirit'' connects his initial reaction to the grief surrounding him with his approach to the grave.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 33, 41, 3, 5, 5, NULL, 'Emotional Response of Jesus', 'This connection highlights Jesus'' emotional responses to human suffering. Both passages depict Jesus experiencing deep feelings—groaning and being troubled in John, and being grieved in Mark—reflecting his compassion for those in pain.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 33, 43, 12, 27, 27, 'and was troubled', 'Connection of Troubled Souls', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of being troubled. In John 11:33, Jesus is troubled by the sorrow around him, while in John 12:27, he expresses his own troubled soul regarding his impending fate.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 33, 45, 12, 15, 15, NULL, 'Empathy in Suffering', 'This connection highlights the shared emotional response to grief. Both passages emphasize the importance of mourning with those who weep.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 33, 1, 43, 30, 31, 'weeping', 'Emotional Responses to Grief', 'This connection highlights the deep emotional responses of both Jesus and Joseph to the suffering of loved ones. Both passages depict a profound sense of sorrow, as seen in the phrases ''weeping'' and ''yearn upon his brother.''', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 33, 1, 45, 1, 5, 'was troubled', 'Emotional Responses to Grief', 'This connection highlights the emotional turmoil experienced by both Jesus and Joseph in response to grief. Both passages depict deep sorrow and a troubled spirit, emphasizing their compassion for those around them.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 33, 41, 9, 19, 19, 'he groaned in the spirit, and was troubled', 'Emotional Response to Suffering', 'Both passages emphasize a deep emotional response to suffering. In John, Jesus is troubled by the weeping around him, while in Mark, he expresses frustration with the lack of faith amidst suffering.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 34, 40, 28, 6, 6, 'come and see', 'Invitation to Witness the Tomb', 'Both passages emphasize an invitation to see the place where the Lord was laid. In John, the question ''Where have ye laid him?'' parallels the invitation in Matthew to ''come, see the place where the Lord lay.''', 'theme', 0.307, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 34, 41, 15, 47, 47, 'where have ye laid him?', 'Connection of Burial Locations', 'This connection highlights the act of laying someone in a tomb. Both passages emphasize the physical location where individuals were laid after death.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
